Homicide & Suicide

Posted 12/6/2018 by Bobby Taylor


Homicide and Suicide these two words are often associated with the feeling of grief. Did you know 1 out of every 200 gun owners uses their own gun to end their life? Although there are many ways homicides and suicides are committed, for this post, I will focus on gun-related deaths. Now, Let's talk about murder. If anyone has had a family member who was a victim of a gun-related homicide, they will understand the mixed emotions of sorrow or guilt which follow.

I will tell you a short story. Once upon a time, I had a cousin. A real fly guy type of character. I remember one time, he wore a button-down zebra printed Versace shirt with some snakeskin boots. Years later, I saw him at a family reunion. We talked for about an hour. After the small talk, we planned a night out on the following Saturday. But, this shindig never happened. I later found out he had been shot and killed on Natural Bridge Road.

Let's fast forward to the next family reunion the following year, I remember seeing his girlfriend and seeing the innocents in his 4-year-old child eyes. I often wondered if the child understood what happened to his father. I am pretty sure the memory of my cousin impelled me to explore this dataset. Let's start exploring.

For this EDA, I decided to explore a dataset which included four types of gun-related deaths. The four categorical variables in the intent column are the following:

  • Accidental
  • Undetermined
  • Homicide
  • Suicide

This EDA will mainly focus on gun-related homicides and suicides. The dataset included 99,414 records and 11 features which unfortunately for me needed scrubbing before the analysis could be completed. After the data was cleaned, I wanted to know a few different questions. The feature names are below.


Feature Names

  • Intent
  • Police
  • Sex
  • Age
  • Race
  • Place
  • Education

Questions

  1. What are the percentage values for each ethnic group involved in a gun-related death?
  2. What is the percentage of gun-related deaths by intent?
  3. What is the central tendency for each ethnic group age distribution for victims involved in either a homicide or suicide?

Question 1: What are the percentage values for each ethnic group involved in a gun-related death?



Question 2: What is the percentage of gun-related deaths by intent?



Question 3: What is the central tendency for each ethnic group age distribution for victims involved in either a homicide or suicide?

  •

Findings:

Overall, I enjoyed performing this EDA. I think the reason I enjoy wrangling through data is to uncover hidden truths. Although the data collected is a sample of the overall United States population, I believe it paints a good picture of America's issues pertaining to gun-related deaths. Lets, look at some of the findings:

  • The data analyzed contained 99,414 gun-related deaths, 63.5% are suicides, and 34% are homicides. Why are some many people committing suicides? Is there a way to lower these percentages? I remember when I was younger, there was a D.A.R.E program in schools. I am not sure if this program still exists, but maybe it would be a good idea to start a suicide prevention program for kids. Just a thought.

  • 87.6% of the suicides in this dataset were committed by Caucasian's. Also, something alarming is the mean, median, and mode are 52, 53, and 54 years old for suicides committed by Caucasian's. When comparing the median to other ethnic groups, there is at least a 10-year difference. What is happening at 50 years old, that is causing these suicides. Is this the adverse effects of ageism? I'm not sure what the solution is to this problem, but its something to question.

  • Now, let's look at the homicide distributions for each ethnic group. African-Americans make up 56.7% of all the homicides, following Caucasian's making up 25%. But, what stood out to me the most was all the age distributions for homicides for each ethnic group are positively skewed. This leads me to believe that younger people, in general, are more susceptible to die from gun-related homicides. Why is this? Is age directly proportional to wisdom? If so, then it would be critical to listen to your elders. Warning, I have met some old fools.

Greater St.Louis Area

Posted 4/19/2018 by Bobby Taylor


As I traveled from the home of Willie Nelson back to the birthplace of Chuck Berry, I started reflecting on the things I've experienced and the people I've encountered. I can tell you leaving St. Louis was a hard decision but necessary. For me, I needed to experience other cities.


Now, I am back in St.louis wondering what should be my next move. So, I decided to explore a dataset I found rambling through the interwebs. In this quick EDA, I used an interactive mapping library, JavaScript, HTML, CSS, and pandas.The records in this dataset were pretty straightforward and no data cleaning was needed. Each record contained eleven features. The features were the following:


Feature Names

  • Municipality
  • Population
  • Sales Tax
  • Fines and Fees
  • FF Per Capita
  • ST per Capita
  • General Revenue
  • FF as Percent of General Revenue
  • Without Sales Tax
  • With Fines and Fees under Cap
  • Best Course

So first, I decided to map the top 10 populated areas in St.Louis and I wanted to know the revenue for each municipality. I was amazed that Florissant had the highest population and University City generated the most revenue.





Next, I decided to group by municipality to visualize the sale tax and fines & fees per capita and the results were startling. It appears Ferguson has the highest sale tax along with fines & fees per capita but generates the lowest revenue and has the smallest population.





Findings:

The goal of this EDA was to practice interactive mapping with a real dataset and learn more about front-end developement. In the process, I discovered a few findings which pose even deeper questions which are outside of my domain. Some of the questions are the following:

  • Why does Ferguson and Maryland Heights have the highest fine & fees per capita and how can St.louis solve this problem?
  • The population size is inversely proportional to the general revenue in Wildwood. Maybe, there needs to be more businesses in this municipality.
  • What are some of the contributing factors in sales tax per capita and how can these values be lowered for all municipalities?
  • How can the general revenue be increased in Wildwood and Ferguson?

WHY...WHY..Create a blog???

Posted 4/18/2018 by Bobby Taylor

The goal of this blog is to visually explore different datasets and provide a summary of my findings. I chose to create this blog for a couple of different reasons.

  • If the old saying, "practice makes perfect" is true, then this will be an excellent medium to practice EDA. Often, I find myself only wanting to know a few different questions when exploring various datasets with nowhere to post my findings. So, I figured creating this blog would be a great place to showcase my results and learn a lot along the way.
  • A good way to practice front-end web development, web applications, and use different interactive mapping libraries.

This blog is pretty standard at this time, but as my skills grow, I will further design the front-end.
